  <span id="freeText8610213632742497359" style="display:none">This book is my nemesis. It's one of those books every Finnish person "should" read for historical and cultural reasons but I just cannot finish it. I've tried seven times. I just can't. It's tedious, and I passionately want to scream at the main character/narrator because of all the idiotic choices he makes. Most of his hardships are chosen by him, and he moans about them forever. I can't stand people who complain and then continue the exact behavior that ruined them in the first place. In Sinuhe's case, this is him thinking that he's different from other people and destined for loneliness, and thus everyone around him either betrays him or gets their lives ruined by his decisions (and he'll complain about it all without much acknowledgment of his part in it all).<br /><br />To say something positive, the book is wonderfully detailed and is very recognizable in style. I like Waltari's writing in general but in this book, it just emphasizes all the issues I have with Sinuhe to the point that I don't think I'll ever have enough discipline to get through the whole thing.</span>
