<span id="freeTextContainer4368520342901365112">Longish classics are somewhat problematic: you&apos;ll be happy to buy them (especially if they are beautiful editions such as this), but they often end up spending years without reading just sitting on your shelf glaring at you disapprovingly with other accumulated peers (at least that&apos;s what it feels like to me). When you finally gather the willpower to start reading them (it is after all much easier to start a 300 page book than, say, 779 page one), there is always the possibility that you find th</span>
  <span id="freeText4368520342901365112" style="display:none">Longish classics are somewhat problematic: you'll be happy to buy them (especially if they are beautiful editions such as this), but they often end up spending years without reading just sitting on your shelf glaring at you disapprovingly with other accumulated peers (at least that's what it feels like to me). When you finally gather the willpower to start reading them (it is after all much easier to start a 300 page book than, say, 779 page one), there is always the possibility that you find the book's classic status much overrated (perhaps more based on its importance during its historical publication than its literary merits).<br /><br />Anyways, thank goodness Sinuhe lived up to its reputation. That is, it was an enjoyable historical novel that was certainly very readable and sometimes even a bit deep in its humanism. Its historical setting was also helped by the feeling of deep personal attachment by the author which was apparent, even without the scrap of knowledge that the novel was written much in a way to exorcise some of the personal demons caused by the WWII. This knowledge did somewhat affect my reading as a whole and once it was in my head it remained with me through the novel. I couldn't help but see the parallels with (especially the Finnish) experience of "the Second Great War" and was a bit reoccupied with wondering how the events of the ancient river Kingdoms and their neighbouring areas were connected with the events of the recent century. Perhaps, this preoccupation was a bit enhanced by some other books I have read during this years, which only goes to show the intertextuality of the reading experience; how you are always reading in a context of both the world, but the literary world as well.<br /><br />Anyways, I did enjoy the book in all its length, somewhat sigh-inducing humour and its slight repetitiveness. It had a heart: a heart that laughed, enjoyed life and almost as a consequence often bled. One could almost feel the distress of a writer torn with disbelief of the humanity he so much loved, at the same time celebrating its flaws as crying over its deep dark recesses that so blatantly had risen in the period before its publication to the fore of the human experience. There is ever darkness waiting for its turn in the human hearts and souls, but there is always hope for better to hold a torch against it advances. Perhaps, that wasn't what mr Waltari wanted to say, but that was what I got, and that is what matters.<br /><br /> </span>
