  <span id="freeText8207753902993203446" style="display:none">I have to say, I was apprehensive when I approached this book. I knew nothing about it in advance except that it's supposed to be some kind of literary classic written in the 1940s. I expected it to be ponderous, boring, high-minded and stuffy. But, book in hand, I thought "why not", took a deep breath, gritted my teeth and dove in. <br /><br />To my surprise I found that this book is anything but boring and stuffy. It is, above all, an entertaining and very human tale that makes ancient Egypt feel like a real place with real people. The characters are all colorfully drawn with a lighthearted, ironic eye, and the book just whooshes by despite it's length. <br /><br />If you can get your hands on Waltari's other books, The Adventurer and The Wanderer, I recommend them as well, as they share the same qualities the make The Egyptian great.</span>
